&lt;button onclick="topFunction()" id="myBtn" title="Go to top">&amp;#11161;&lt;/button>
&lt;script>
let mybutton = document.getElementById("myBtn");
window.onscroll = function() {scrollFunction()};
function scrollFunction() {
if (document.body.scrollTop > 20 || document.documentElement.scrollTop > 20) {
mybutton.style.display = "block";
} else {
mybutton.style.display = "none";
}
}
function topFunction() {
document.body.scrollTop = 0;
document.documentElement.scrollTop = 0;
}
&lt;/script>
&lt;p>A linked list is a sequential data structure. A head pointer points to the
first node and each node has a pointer to the next. The last node is suitably
terminated. Manipulating a linked list is an exact exercise and reversing it
certainly so. Would a cutaway view be helpful?&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>